07479nam a22011055i 9783110261523DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20122012gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013955584  a97831102615237 a10.1515/97831102615232doi  a(DE-B1597)171904  a(OCoLC)900723119  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481ua414.6qDE-101222/ger04aThe Sonority Controversy /ced. by Steve Parker. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (487 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhonology and Phonetics [PP] ,x1861-4191 ;v180 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSonority has a long and contentious history. It has often been invoked by linguists as an explanatory principle underlying various cross-linguistic phonotactic generalizations, especially within the domain of the syllable. However, many phonologists and phoneticians have expressed concerns about the adequacy of formal accounts based on sonority, including even doubts about the very existence of sonority itself. To date, the topic of sonority has never been the focus of an entire book. Consequently, this is the first complete volume that explores diverging viewpoints about phonological phenomena rooted in sonority taken from numerous languages. All of the contributors are well-known and respected linguists who publish their research in leading academic outlets. Furthermore, each chapter in this collection contains new, cutting-edge results based on the latest trends in the field. Hence, no other extant piece of literature matches this volume in terms of its breadth and coverage of issues, all converging on the common theme of sonority. Given the wide variety of subtopics in this collection, there is something to appeal to everyone - the list of contributions encompasses areas such as Optimality Theory, acquisition, computational modeling, acoustic phonetics, typology, syllable structure, speech perception, markedness, connectionism, psycholinguistics, and even MRI technology. What ties all of these issues together is a solid and consistent emphasis on sonority as a unified background phenomenon. Furthermore, a continuum of opinions about sonority is represented, ranging from complete acceptance and enthusiasm, on the one hand, to moderate skepticism on the other hand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aPhonetics.  aPhonology.  aProsody.  aSpeech Production and Perception.1 aBaer-Henney, Dinah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaertsch, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBat-El, Outi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCser, András, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFry, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhushchyan, Edita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenke, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJantunen, Tommi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaisse, Ellen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonnell, Bradley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Brett, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreton, Elliott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Steve, eedi